| rev3      = ''[[The New York Times]]''
| rev3score = positive<ref name="nyt-rockwell">{{cite journal |last=Rockwell |first=John |authorlink=John Rockwell |date=November 8, 1981 |title=New York's Experimental Music Sounds Familiar Notes |url=http://www.nytimes.com/1981/11/08/arts/new-york-s-experimental-music-sounds-familiar-notes.html |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=A19 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>
| rev4      = ''[[NME]]''
| rev4score = 9/10<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pattison |first=Louis |date=June 14, 2003 |title=Reviews |url=http://www.glennbranca.com/reviews_asc.html |journal=[[NME]] |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>
| rev5      = [[Pitchfork Media]]
| rev5score = 10/10<ref name="pitchfork-beta"/>
| rev6      = [[Tiny Mix Tapes]]
| rev6score = positive<ref name="tmt-mahoney"/>
}}
Upon its initial release, ''The Ascension'' received positive reviews from music critics.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sterritt |first=David |authorlink=David Sterritt |date=May 24, 1982 |title=Branca's radical music is claimed by two camps <U+2014> rock and classical |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1982/0524/052403.html |journal=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> In a review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[John Rockwell]] wrote that ''The Ascension'' did a better job than ''Lesson No. 1'' of capturing the impact of Branca's live concerts but that "his work may be too grand and loud ever to be captured on disk."<ref name="nyt-rockwell"/> It ranked the album 6th on its list of the best albums of 1981.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Palmer |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Palmer (writer) |date=December 30, 1981 |title=The Pop Life |url=http://www.nytimes.com/1981/12/30/arts/the-pop-life-155232.html |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=C9 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> [[Kristine McKenna]] wrote in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' that the album "does a surprisingly good job of conveying the awesome power of his live performance<U+2026>[it] lacks the glorious dimension of Branca's live show, but is good enough to serve as an introduction to a major new talent."<ref>{{cite journal |last=McKenna |first=Kristine |authorlink=Kristine McKenna |date=July 10, 1982 |title=Pop Beat: New York's Noise Bands |journal=[[Los Angeles Times]] |page=E4}}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]'' writer [[Robert Christgau]] described the album as "great sonically" but continued that "the beat's overstated and the sense of structure<U+2026>mired in nineteenth-century corn."<ref name="christgau"/> In the 1981 [[Pazz & Jop]] list, compiled by Christgau based on a survey of several hundred critics, ''The Ascension'' placed 51st.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau |date=February 1, 1982 |title=The Year the Rolling Stones Lost the Pennant |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/pj81.php |journal=[[The Village Voice]] |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>

Since its original release, the album has garnered critical acclaim. [[Pitchfork Media]] awarded it a perfect 10.0 score.<ref name="pitchfork-beta"/> ''[[XLR8R]]'' commented that "if these recordings pale in comparison to the live experience, [they] are no less rapturous for it."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xlr8r.com/reviews/2003/07/the-ascension/ |title=Glenn Branca ''The Ascension'' |last=Georgopoulos |first=Alexis |date=July 4, 2003 |website=[[XLR8R]] |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> [[AllMusic]] called it "one of the greatest rock albums ever made", adding that its "sonic experimentation" was more in the tradition of avant-garde musicians [[La Monte Young]] and [[Phill Niblock]].<ref name="allmusic-olewnick"/>  [[Tiny Mix Tapes]] said that ''The Ascension'' diverges from punk and classical traditions "as simply essential 20th-century music."<ref name="tmt-mahoney"/> ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]'' magazine ranked the album 8th on its list of the best albums of the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.factmag.com/2013/06/24/the-100-best-albums-of-the-1980s-100-81/84/ |title=The 100 Best Albums of the 1980s |date=June 24, 2013 |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |access-date=February 9, 2015}}</ref>

==Release and impact==
''The Ascension'' was released through [[Ed Bahlman]]'s label 99 Records. Bahlman sold over 10,000 copies out of his shop on [[MacDougal Street]] in [[Manhattan, New York]], and the vinyl copies became a rare collector's item.<ref name="allmusic-olewnick"/><ref>Foege 1994, p. 37</ref> Although the album was successful for an independent release, it did not receive any interest from major labels.<ref>Masters 2007, p. 130</ref> New Tone Records re-released the album on CD in 1999, and Acute Records re-released it in 2003 with old footage of Branca performing in the apartment of his [[Theoretical Girls]] bandmate Jeffrey Lohn.<ref name="allmusic-olewnick"/><ref>Chick 2009</ref> ''The Ascension'' has remained Branca's most popular album.<ref name="village-voice-cohan">{{cite web |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2010-02-23/music/glenn-branca-ascends-anew/full/ |title=Glenn Branca Ascends Anew |last=Cohan |first=Brad |date=February 23, 2010 |website=[[The Village Voice]] |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Branca released a sequel titled ''The Ascension: The Sequel'' in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/post/127826-glenn-branca-the-ascension-the-sequel/ |title=Glenn Branca: The Ascension: The Sequel |last=Garratt |first=John |date=July 6, 2010 |website=[[PopMatters]] |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> To do so, he re-established [[Neutral Records]] under its original name Systems Neutralizers.<ref name="village-voice-cohan"/>

''The Ascension'' influenced the work of Sonic Youth and [[Swans (band)|Swans]].<ref>Earles 2014, p. 49</ref> Kurt Kellison encountered the album in 1984 and said, "I haven't thought about music the same way ever since." After founding [[Atavistic Records]], Kellison released some of Branca's later guitar symphonies.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Kot |first=Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot |date=February 5, 1995 |title=Transcendental Innovation |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-02-05/entertainment/9502050033_1_lower-manhattan-music-guitar |journal=[[Chicago Tribune]] |page=12 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] referenced the cover artwork for [[LCD Soundsystem]]'s 2010 album ''[[This Is Happening]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/190118-glenn-branca-the-ascension/ |title=Glenn Branca: The Ascension |last=Mathers |first=Ian |date=February 3, 2015 |website=[[PopMatters]] |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>

